         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translation</head>
            <p>To the gods of the dead. Marcus Aurelius Apollonius, 
                    veteran of the 2nd Legion Adiutrix, of the arms factory, has
                    built this tomb for himself and his household in his life-time. (Reynolds)</p></div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>line 1. The name perhaps suggests a man of non-Roman status
                recruited into the legion under Marcus or Commodus.</p>
            <p>l.2. The name of the legion, previously misread as XV 
                    Apollinaris, is clear enough, although at first glance obscured
                    by damage to the stone. The suggestion of Rossberg, taken up 
                    by Applebaum, that Apollonius was one of the colonists sent 
                    to repopulate Cyrenaica after the Jewish Revolt must be rejected
                    both because of the probable date of the text and of the disappearance 
                    of the supposed connexion with legion XV Apollinaris.</p>
            <p>Legion II 
                    Adiutrix was stationed at Aquincum in Pannonia from the early 
                    II century onwards.</p>
            <p>l.3. Apollonius had a post as trainer in the legionary arms factory; for the title in the same legion cf. CIL III.10516.</p>
            <p>l.4. The size of the tomb and the quality of the inscription 
                    suggest a man of substance though not wealthy enough for real grandeur.
                    </p><p>See further Reynolds, art. cit.</p>
         </div>
         
